<p>Solar installation costs in Oregon have decreased significantly over the past decade, with current prices ranging from \$2.75 to \$3.45 per watt before incentives. These costs include high-quality tier-one solar panels, inverters, mounting systems, electrical components, permits, and professional installation. The variation in pricing depends on factors such as roof complexity, equipment selection, installer experience, and local permit requirements.</p>

<h2>HVAC Systems in Oregon</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Oregon's climate presents unique HVAC requirements due to its diverse microclimates and changing weather patterns. Western Oregon experiences a marine climate with mild, wet winters and warm, dry summers, while eastern Oregon has a more continental climate with greater temperature variations. Average winter temperatures in Portland range from 35-45¬∞F, requiring efficient heating systems, while summer temperatures increasingly reach 85-95¬∞F, making cooling systems essential for comfort.</p>

<p>The state's humidity levels vary dramatically by season and region, with western areas experiencing high humidity during winter months and very low humidity during summer. This variability requires HVAC systems capable of managing both temperature and humidity control effectively. Modern heat pump systems are particularly well-suited to Oregon's climate, as they provide efficient heating and cooling while handling moderate temperature ranges effectively.</p>

<p>Climate change has increased the importance of cooling systems in Oregon, with record-breaking heat waves becoming more frequent. The 2021 Pacific Northwest heat dome, which brought temperatures above 115¬∞F to Portland, highlighted the critical need for reliable cooling systems. Additionally, wildfire smoke has made air filtration and indoor air quality management increasingly important considerations for HVAC system selection.</p>

